y. Authors chart the roles played by diverse groups—criminals and peace officers, entrepreneurs and miners, farmers and public officials, defenders of discrimination and female and African American activists. The essays also explore subjects largely overlooked in the past, such as the significance of local and federal government in pioneer California and early struggles to secure civil rights for women and racial minorities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aFrontier and pioneer lifexCalifornia. 0aFrontier and pioneer lifezCalifornia. 0aLawxHistoryx19th centuryxCalifornia. 0aLawzCaliforniaxHistoryy19th century. 0aLegislationxHistoryx19th centuryxCalifornia. 0aLegislationzCaliforniaxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / West (AK, CA, CO, HI, ID, MT, NV, UT, WY).2bisacsh  aamerica.  acalifornia history.  acalifornia politics.  acalifornia society.  acalifornia.  acivil rights.  acultural diversity.  acultural history.  aearly inhabitants.  aenvironmental change.  aessay collection.  aethnic studies.  afrontier experience.  agold rush.  agovernment agencies.  agovernment and governing.  ahistorians.  ajurisprudence.  anonfiction essays.  apioneer period.  apioneers.  apolitical history.  apublic policy.  aregional history.  astate formation.  atextbooks.  aunited states.  aus history.1 aBakken, Gordon Morris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBecker, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurns, John F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurns, John F., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChandler, Robert J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrenier,